content.description: Cool route that is sporty right at the crux.  Dirty start to ledge then make odd move into short corner with nice crack.  At big horizontal the business begins.  Make stiff moves either right or left up into tricky side pull and sketchy three cam placement.  Stay right of arete above.  There is a nice finger lock above that's nice for a gear placement too (just below top).  Semi jugs to be gotten above the crux but it is still hard due to little feet.
content.protection: Excellent gear placements except at the crux.  You have got a good run-out at the crux although great gear at the horizontal.
content.location: Steep corner and arete just right of the prominent corner route Bloodshed.

content.description: Start under overhang , interesting moves lead to an easy finish in the dihedral.
content.protection: Minimal protection. Easy TR set up off large pine at the top of the route.
content.location: Far left side of Red  Nose wall.

content.description: Climb to ledge. From the ledge, climb upper overhanging wall left of Cutting Edge.
content.location: On the left-most end of the southeast-facing wall of Red Nose.

content.description: Practice your stemming on this short inside corner. It has some useful cracks and edges on the left side, but not so much on the right.This is the unnamed inside corner #18 in Swartling/Mayer.
content.protection: nearby cracks and a tree for the top anchor
content.location: On the left side of the rock face that is north of the main Red Nose wall and separated from it by an access route to the bottom of the walls.

content.description: Climb to ledge. From the ledge, climb narrow face left of Bloodshed. Of course you may not use the Bloodshed crack.
content.location: On the southeast-facing wall of Red Nose, above the ledge and left of the dihedral.

content.description: Start in the shallow inside corner to the right of the large detached block, then continue in the crack above.
content.protection: large rocks and cracks for building top anchor.
content.location: On the left (west) side of the south-facing wall just a few feet right of the large detached block.

content.description:
Start up the crack with a layback. Don't use the block that's a couple feet left of the crack or you'll spoil the fun. Pass the overhang on the right and climb the southeast corner and face left of the corner.

 This is the unnamed route #8 in Swartling/Mayer.
content.protection: You'll need long rope or webbing to reach rocks and trees for this top anchor.
content.location: On the protruding section of rock on the right (east) end of the south facing wall. If you walk from the south-east facing wall to the south-facing wall you can walk through a narrow passage in the rocks and you will see Passage Crack as you exit the passage.

content.description: Big ol' crux to gain the slab! Climb the "down-sloping projections" with thin corner crack to gain the slab, then traverse left to a nice no hands ledge then up a small dihedral to the top.
content.protection: Small pro on the crack, ball-nuts or brassies are very helpful.
content.location: 15ft right of Wounded Knee.

content.description: Climb the flaring crack, looks harder than it is.
content.location: East face of the "MANcation" block up the hill a bit NE of the East side of Red Nose Wall.

content.description: Good moves all the way.
content.location: Above the east section of Red Nose Wall is this separate block with a few great routes. MANcation is the crack layback system on the left side of the front face.

content.description: Climb the overhanging wall and grove between October Country and Breaking Away.
content.location: On the right end of the southeast-facing wall of Red Nose just left of the inside corner.

content.description:
You might wish this slightly inclined wall had a bit more lean to it. Climb the narrow face between Elimination and A Girl Named Sue. Starts out OK, then the fun starts as you get above the wide horizontal crack. Finish just right of notch.

 It is difficult to climb without drifting to nearby easier holds on either side. It seems a bit contrived since it is hard to figure what holds are on and off. If you think it's easier than 5.10a, then you probably cheated.

 This is the unnamed route #5 in Swartling/Mayer.
content.location: In the middle of the south-facing wall.

content.description: Climb to the right side of the ledge (same start as Wounded Knee). From the ledge, climb up and right to a small platform while trying not to laugh. Finish in the hanging left-facing inside corner.
content.location: On the southeast-facing wall of Red Nose, above the right-most end of the ledge.

content.description: Climb the face using a series of lay-backs and long reaches.
content.protection: You'll need long rope or webbing to reach rocks and trees for this top anchor.
content.location: There is a protruding section of rock on the right (east) end of the south-facing wall. Judgement Day is on the west face of this protruding rock.

content.description: Easy crack climb with somewhat dubious rock quality. Makes for a decent warm up.
content.location: Located at far west end of Red Nose Wall. Obvious crack on left side of wall.

content.description: Climb 4 ft to the ledge, then climb the awkward inside corner to top.
content.protection: Nearby trees and rocks for top anchor.
content.location: On the south-facing wall. This is the 4 ft deep left-facing dihedral located on the west end of the wall behind a large detached block and left of White Wasp.

content.description: Dirty start, good gear, fun moves, and maybe a bit under-rated in Swartling's guide.  Crux is obvious slight overhang.
content.location: To be found right side of the central wall of Red Nose Wall.  Walk down like any DL route.

content.description: Starts easy enough, then cruxs hard halfway up.
content.location: Right of MANcation on the separate block NE of the East side of Red Nose Wall. Go up the obvious water streak.

content.description: Crux is first 20 feet. It's steep but with a lot of options for the feet and large jugs.  Make slight step left (into upper part of "Look Ma- No Hands" route after the crux to make it more protectable and easier).
content.protection: All natural gear- cams are good and quick.   Nice large pine tree at top to make quick decent from or else walk down.
content.location: Right most prominent and steep corner of the Red Nose Wall proper.

content.description: Good holds in the dihedral with fun laybacking. Climb the lower face to the grassy ledge and then go up in the dihedral to the roof, then go left into the next dihedral. Try the direct which goes right at the roof and uses the arete above the roof.
content.location: West side of Red Nose Wall. Find the big triangular roof.

content.description: Climb face and shallow crack 8 feet left of inside corner.
content.protection: nearby rocks and cracks for top anchor
content.location: A protruding section of rock on the right (east) side of the south-facing wall forms a junky inside corner. A Girl Named Sue is on the south-facing wall 8' left of the inside corner.

pathTokens: East Bluff 03 - West of the Quarry

content.description: Part of West of Quarry Rocks- upper part of West Ridge outcropping, right side of West Cwm boulder field- routes are about 40 to 50 ft in height.  Many good gear leads here although routes can be a bit damp and dusty.
